In determining whether payments were interest or dividends, for purposes of Internal Revenue Code provision permitting deduction of interest paid or accrued during taxable year, courts consider several factors, including whether corporation is so grossly undercapitalized that loans are in fact needed for capital purposes and are actually intended to be risk capital rather than loan; whether purported loans were made in proportion to equity holdings; whether repayment of loan was predicated on success of venture; whether there was fixed date for payment of note and reasonable expectation of payment by that date; whether obligation to pay was subordinated to other corporate debts; whether third parties would have made loan under same conditions; whether claimed loan was secured by mortgage or otherwise; whether provision was made for sinking fund to retire loan; whether person making purported loan participated in management of corporation; and whether corporation had large proportion of debt to equity. 
